The Letters

<2020-09-29 Tue>

Figure 1: Image of two TV monitors at an airport, showing two different TV networks spinning the same news item in different ways. Sourced from Instagram

Scott Adams, the famed creator of the comic strip “Dilbert,” an expert in the psychology of persuasion, and apparently a master of spotting satanic symbolism 1 likes to quip that Americans are watching two different movies on the same screen. A cliched statement perhaps, familiar to most in some alternative forms. “America is two nations ruled by a single party,” is another one that comes to mind. Assertions such as these seldom give listeners the requisite pause. After all, every American is already aware that <INSERT NEWS SOURCE HERE> is biased 2, and that their favorite sources always disagree with the aforementioned. All specific examples against one’s media preferences are easily disregarded as cherry-picked, unfortunate instances not representative of the general trend. And upon being pressed further, the entire concern over media bias is dismissed as a meta discussion not worthy of our attention, especially when contrasted with the more important, and immediate issue of <INSERT CURRENT AFFAIRS TOPIC HERE>.

Even if content with a personally curated media diet, I’d suggest to the reader that the persistent and worsening partisan divide in the population is the most pressing issue of all. And given how dendritic the influence of news media on our perception is 3, understanding this phenomena and guarding against it is a necessary step to healing the wounds and building bridges. Failure at this project will result in a serious erosion of trust in all of our institutions, and in each other. We are arguably already paying the price for it.

Figure 3: Contrasting headlines published on the New York Post and The Hill

A House Divided

The Two Towers

The fundamental difference between liberals and conservatives comes down to this: the former underestimate both the value of existing structures and the negative consequences of new proposals, while the latter overestimate them. The full nature/nurture debate on what makes an individual either of these is beyond the scope of this letter. The labels seem to often fall short in utility for describing most concepts. Consequently, people like inventing new terms (left/right) or appending adjectives (socially liberal, fiscally conservative) 4. Some try to add orthogonal axes and create D&D alignment charts, like the Politcal Compass, a two-dimensional graph with the x-axis representing the left/right divide, and the y-axis standing in for “authoritarianism” vs “libertarianism” 5. Still others attempt to generate triangular radar maps 6.

Such esoteric exercises are best left to academics with too much time on their hands. What is of concern here is how a population has changed over time in terms of their beliefs. Most longitudinal measurements have stuck to the left/right or liberal/conservative uni-axial metric. Comparing data across studies has obvious pitfalls. Different research groups use different definitions, sample different subpopulations, and rely on self-identification (which is dicey since terms change meaning over time). But the trends in all such measurements (given the above caveats) all indicated a nation that continues to divide. Said worsening divide is reflected in the composition of elected officials, as was aptly illustrated by the following plot published by The Economist in 2018 (See also 7).

Figure 4: Increasing polarization among House candidates. Source: The Economist.

Based on Prof. Adam Bonica’s metrics, elected officials on the right have–in aggregate–consolidated towards a core set of positions. The variance on the blue distribution on the other hand has increased enough to reveal a three-peaked substructure within (perhaps indicative of clustering along some orthogonal axes). Also worth noting that the mean of the blue curve shifts away from the 1980 median more than the red mean does. And the rate of the drift becomes more extreme in the 2000s’. This same trend was observed in an analysis of Party Manifestos published by the New York Times:

Figure 5: Party manifesto political leanings. Source: New York Times

It used to be the case in American politics that after spending the weekdays professing platitudes to the press, politicians from both sides of the aisle would get together with their families on weekend retreats at country estates to socialize and hash out their legislative differences. Despite their opposing ideologies, everyone was said to share a common patriotism, no doubt in response to an external threat. This is said to have stopped occurring somewhere in the 90s’.

One would naively guess that the polarization in the party must reflect a similar effect in the US population. But this is not so. One has to separate the “politically engaged” from the “less engaged” to recover the trend towards the extremes:

Figure 6: Differential Polarization in the population based on level of political engagement. Source: Pew Research Center

While we still see that the later years have seen an increase in the rate of polarization compared to earlier decades in both subpopulations (no doubt due in part to technology and social media), it is clear that the people with the more extreme views (14% when counting both sides, according to The Hidden Tribes report) are driving policy decisions.

Fear and Loathing

If only the extremes (or the “politically engaged”) are who determine the bounds of discourse (see Overton Window), then is it any surprise that a majority of Americans have political views that they are afraid to share publicly:

Figure 7: CATO institute Survey of American comfort-level with sharing political opinions.

Admittedly, the CATO institute is a Koch funded “right-wing” think tank. And if these letters are reaching the right in-group, this should bias most readers against taking the above plot at face value. But seldom do we pause to consider what effect a left/liberal majority in institutional composition has on our media, academy, and entertainment industry. How would this impact knowledge production and narrative? Imagine if Wikipedia partnered with Google and Amazon to tailor the content on its page to suit your tastes based on your search and online-purchasing history. Now wonder how the political leanings of the editors (including whole armies that host “edit-a-thon” parties) are distributed.

We see similar alarming trends in the media 8 and academia 9, 10. The homogeneity problem in academia is worse in non-STEM fields, where the ratio in some departments can range from 50:1 to 108:0 across, say, in a bunch of liberal-arts colleges in New England 10.

Figure 8: Self-identification of undergraduate teaching faculty in the US across time. Source: Sam Abrams at Heterodox Academy. Data from HERI (UCLA). The same plot for the general population does not show significant change over time, thus accounting for changing definitions of terms.

My peers often try to justify these observations by suggesting that the left/liberal paradigm has always been an agent of positive social change, and has never gotten it wrong. To this, I have often countered with an accusation of selection bias, and have deployed the watchman principle 11. However, this letter does not concern with the rights and wrongs of ideological positions. It is only concerned with the effect of polarization on stability of society and institutions. The very fact that a population has identified itself under (at least) two tribal banners has terrible consequences, especially considering our primitive instincts.

Consider the following excerpt from The Righteous Mind by Prof. Jonathan Haidt:

When I speak to liberal audiences about the three “binding” foundations – Loyalty, Authority, Sanctity – I find that many in the audience don’t just fail to resonate; they actively reject these concerns as immoral. Loyalty to a group shrinks the moral circle; it is the basis of racism and exclusion, they say. Authority is oppression. Sanctity is religious mumbo-jumbo whose only function is to suppress female sexuality and justify homophobia.

In a study I did with Jesse Graham and Brian Nosek, we tested how well liberals and conservatives could understand each other. We asked more than two thousand American visitors to fill out the Moral Foundations Questionnaire. One-third of the time they were asked to fill it out normally, answering as themselves. One-third of the time they were asked to fill it out as they think a “typical liberal” would respond. One-third of the time they were asked to fill it out as a “typical conservative” would respond. This design allowed us to examine the stereotypes that each side held about the other. More important, it allowed us to assess how accurate they were by comparing people’s expectations about “typical” partisans to the actual responses from partisans on the left and the right. Who was best able to pretend to be the other?

The results were clear and consistent. Moderates and conservatives were most accurate in their predictions, whether they were pretending to be liberals or conservatives. Liberals were the least accurate, especially those who described themselves as “very liberal.” The biggest errors in the whole study came when liberals answered the Care and Fairness questions while pretending to be conservatives. When faced with questions such as “One of the worst things a person could do is hurt a defenseless animal” or “Justice is the most important requirement for a society,” liberals assumed that conservatives would disagree. If you have a moral matrix built primarily on intuitions about care and fairness (as equality), and you listen to the Reagan [i.e., conservative] narrative, what else could you think? Reagan seems completely unconcerned about the welfare of drug addicts, poor people, and gay people. He’s more interested in fighting wars and telling people how to run their sex lives.

– Jonathan Haidt, The Righteous Mind, page 334

In summary, conservatives are better at predicting liberal values than liberals are at predicting conservative ones 12. The mutual caricatures amounted to conservatives assuming that liberals were naive and misguided fools, and liberals assuming that conservatives were thick and uncaring brutes. This study was published in 2012, and it would not surprise me if this asymmetry is found to have shrunken by now, if the demonizing popular rhetoric in the media is anything to go by. Proving a causal link between the perception gap and the news media is a hard task, but strong correlations have already been cataloged:

Figure 9: Increase in perception gap related to media consumption. Source: More in Common.

Figure 10: Popular media classified by the perception gaps in their audience. Source: More in Common.

The problem is worse within our in-group. It has long been known that people self-segregate at the geographic 13 and online-association levels. This sort of clustering affects our children’s development when growing up in homogeneous neighborhoods and schools, and being exposed to a very limited set of ideas and lifestyles. The information-sorting algorithms we rely on to curate our daily feeds do not help either. And the longer we are steeped in the fairly exclusionary social cultures of academia, the more isolated we become:

Figure 11: Friendship diversity vs education level for both self-identified party affiliations. Source: More in Common.

Eye on the ball

At the time of this writing, the effect of polarization is most starkly on display in the hysteria over the nomination of a Justice of the Supreme Court to replace the late Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg. Whatever your opinions on the timing of the process, I hope it is visible to the reader that in the eyes of the people today, the Supreme Court has been imbued with more power than the constitution allows. The court is being treated as a second legislature, and it’s Justices (all of whom are extremely well studied and experienced in the legal profession) are being expected by the public to “make law” rather than render judgments on legality of claims and cases 14, 15.

Today, Justice Ginsburg is respected and celebrated by liberals and conservatives alike, and should really be a symbol for national unity. When the Senate confirmed her nomination in 1993 with a 96-3 majority vote, she had the following exchange with the press:

Inviting questions, Judge Ginsburg got this one: “You’ve been called a liberal, you’ve been called a conservative, you’ve been called a moderate. What are you?”

Borrowing pointedly from the Gilbert and Sullivan operetta “Iolanthe,” she replied, to the apparent confusion of the White House press corps, “I don’t believe that every child that’s born alive is either a little liberal or else a little conservative, except in Gilbert and Sullivan.”

– New York Times, 1993

Her obituary on the NYT published this week reveals this gem:

… [RBG] prized collegiality and whose friendship with conservative colleagues on the federal appeals court where she had served for 13 years left some feminist leaders fretting privately that the president [Clinton] was making a mistake.

– New York Times, 2020

The great sin of political polarization is that it turns every election into an existential crisis with the highest possible stakes. This forces everyone to compromise on nearly all of their cherished positions in order to defeat the greater evil. It is a trap that many vested interests (both domestic and foreign) would like perpetuated ad infinitum. Breaking free of it and bringing the country closer together is the real existential objective.

A Balanced Diet

The problem we are facing is very complex, influenced by a variety of factors, and has been metastasizing for at least two decades. The solutions (whatever they may be) would probably take just as long, if not more, to implement. The data presented in the previous section appears to suggest that we might be able to start chipping away at this if we work to reduce the perception gap. In normal, non-pandemic times, I would recommend cultural-exchange programs within the country, wherein urban and rural youth volunteer to work in each other’s communities over some summers. Even as adults, we should generally make it a habit to drive out to rural America, ask questions, and learn to listen.

There is no guarantee that the perception gap can be completely closed. There is very little data on its change over time. And humans can certainly have genuine, irreconcilable differences. The objective is not to agree on positions, but to be able to accurately gauge positions instead of falling back on caricatures and strawmen. There is a debating format in which, after the opening statement, each contestant has to summarize their opponent’s position to the opponents satisfaction. That is what we are aiming for.

“He who knows only his own side of the case knows little of that. His reasons may be good, and no one may have been able to refute them. But if he is equally unable to refute the reasons on the opposite side, if he does not so much as know what they are, he has no ground for preferring either opinion… Nor is it enough that he should hear the opinions of adversaries from his own teachers, presented as they state them, and accompanied by what they offer as refutations. He must be able to hear them from persons who actually believe them…he must know them in their most plausible and persuasive form.”

–John Stuart Mill, On Liberty

There is a postmodern conceit that recommends that we resign ourselves to our biases. That there is no means for arguments to stand on their own merits, and that the only way to advocate for positions is to get our tribal confederates into positions of power. Thousands of years of legal practice has provided us with a way out. In a trial, despite the lack of complete information, we appoint agents (lawyers) who are explicitly and openly biased towards their clients. And we squeeze the marrow of truth out of their deliberately adversarial interactions. This is precisely how democratic legislative bodies are structured as well. The system is far from bulletproof, and can be corrupted. But this is the best we have been able to invent. So let’s run with it.

Media preferences

Much digital ink has been spilt over the partisan divide among the major news networks. Republicans tend to cluster around fewer news networks than democrats, who seem to spread out more.

Figure 12: Partisan divide among viewers of mainstream News networks. Source: Pew Research Center.

In general, republicans are more distrustful of news networks (and indeed, any institutions) than democrats are:

Figure 13: The trust differential across party lines. Source: Pew Research Center.

While Murdoch’s Fox network is touted as the most popular news channel in America, the figures used to justify that obscure some underlying substructure. The conservative distrust of institutions extends to Fox as well. It is only certain individuals on Fox who draw on large audiences. And the actual viewership figures when non-mainstream news sources are included, should reveal that the “spread” among conservatives across multiple sources is comparable to those of liberals.

Some of you may have already attempted to look into alternative perspectives by plugging into the Fox News App over a weekend. This probably ended badly, with frayed nerves and new things to complain about every hour. And the experience might have further entrenched your biases towards favorite sources. I would suggest that there may be a smarter way to do this. The whole “trusting-individuals-over-corporations” thing is a good principle to be aware of, and should definitely inform our exploratory feed construction.

Tricks of the Trade

“So why have optics been so successful in overtaking legacy reality of late? I believe that for a variety of reasons, we have changed what would be called the recursion depth, were we in computer science here rather than the politics of civil society.”

“… we can be easily fooled into thinking we understand a situation by not carrying out an investigation beyond a certain limit. In fact, we cannot afford to give infinite attention and resources to investigating every problem. And so we must cut off our investigations at some point. Some time between 1971, when Herb Simon began thinking about Attention Economics, and 2001 when the Attention Economy concept finally gained enough momentum from Davenport, Beck, and others to propel it into greater mainstream awareness, a huge opportunity was missed. That opportunity was the study of the corresponding market for inattention.”

“For example, in the news-media business many people think that there is always a search for the most eyeballs. Yet there also rose a concept called, ‘The Friday Newsdump’, which sought to find the spot in the week where people would give the least attention to the dissemination of bad news. Likewise, print-media writers learnt to hide their true underlying stories by burying the lead, when the main story had to be told but was not favorable to the paper’s way of thinking. This would sometimes be handled, in what is internally called the ‘to be sure’ paragraph, where the author too often effectively confesses the mitigating truths that they had hoped to avoid, at least until the penultimate paragraph many layers deep.”

“Well, what happens when you can actually calculate where your audience will stop reading, listening, feeling, or thinking? Studies have suggested that just over half of all people spend fifteen seconds or less reading an article while digitally grazing. Likewise, nearly three out of five link sharers have not so much as clicked on the headline that they are passing on. … This however, creates a fantastic opportunity to those whose ethics are sufficiently flexible.”

“A particular form of our five-word law when applied to news media would be, ‘the headline generates the story,’ or ‘the headline is the story.’ Once this has been discovered, we see that increasingly, the purpose of the article in our era is not to inform, but to minimally support the desired headline for wide dissemination. Other forms of this principle are that, at least in the eyes of the weak and the dim, ‘the slogan is the platform,’ ‘accusation generates its own conviction,’ ‘the indignation is the refutation,’ ‘swarms generate their own consensus,’ ‘the messenger is the message,’ and ‘the aspiration is the implementation.’”

…

“Increasingly, there will be a war on anyone found to be attempting to traffic in higher recursion limits.”

–Eric Weinstein, The Portal Podcast

Everybody lies. But most don’t lie when they don’t have to. As you begin growing your exploratory feed, you should start to cultivate a meditative mindset wherein the information (and the format) you encounter is no longer treated as revelation, but as an object to be studied. This will help you develop a healthy skeptical eye which considers and analyses the incentives and motivations of personalities, corporate overlords, advertisers, and platforms when interpreting media. As you begin to catch on to the tricks of the trade, you will eventually be able to apply the whole framing to your primary news feed as well.

A comprehensive catalog of all of the ways the media manipulates us is impossible to compose. At the very least, it would be difficult to use examples from current affairs because the news is rapidly evolving, and detailed dissection takes time and effort. It might be more efficient to explore them as part of analyses of individual topics. The best I can do is pick one or two “tricks” per letter.

In this letter, I’d like to highlight http://newsdiffs.org/. NewsDiffs was the result of an MIT hackathon project in 2012, and is meant to automatically track changes made to the top (as in front page) articles on five major news sites: The New York Times, CNN, Politico, Washington Post, and BBC. I highly encourage browsing through some of their highlighted records.

NewsDiffs is very limited in its scope, in that it only tracks changes to front page (landing page) articles, and only while they are list on said front pages. And only on those five websites. The problem it highlights is called stealth editing, wherein articles get manipulated without an editor’s note acknowledging the edit (one can however force an editor’s note to appear by drawing mainstream attention to particularly egregious instances). This practice is very rampant, even at esteemed news networks, and mostly never gets tracked. It functions as a sinister means of steering public sentiment, because the first and most inaccurate version of any given news article is the one that gets shared and discussed the most, and a later stealth edit covers them from legal and moral liability. So our news feed has to include adversarial agents who can keep an eye on each other for this layer of journalism to be made visible to us 16. This is also the reason that links to most articles in this letter redirect you to a dated snapshot of the actual websites in question on the Internet Archive’s Wayback Machine. Many alternative archival sites exist (such as https://archive.is/), and they are frequently used in online subcultures to share specific/dated versions of articles.

Apply pressure to stop bleeding

Let us remind ourselves that the objective here is to decrease the perception gap. Our description of the other camp has to match its average inhabitants, and not their extremes. Accomplishing this will not make any substantial change in your positions or voting preferences in the short term, but with enough numbers, I think this has great long-term benefits.

If I am hitting the correct in-group readership here, I trust that most of you have primary feeds consisting of, perhaps, some regular New York Times, daily PBS news hour, and the weekend NPR. In growing your secondary, exploratory feeds, keep in mind that some of your tendrils will dip into non-mainstream or alternative sources, which by their very nature will be maligned by your trusty primary feed. This is okay, and in fact desirable. The exploratory feed is meant to be forever shifting and changing, and mutual disagreement (perhaps even malice) among its entities is a measure of the diversity of opinions and viewpoints. Ground.News, for instance, as a nifty "Bias Distribution" infographic that tracks all of the other agencies that are carrying any particular story, along with their respective political leanings (at least as classified by Ground.News). NewsGuard is a third party service/browser plugin that rates various News services on some standard metrics. Again, it is important to not wholly trust any of these, but definitely remain exposed to their assessments. And who knows? Some day, one or two discoveries might influence a change in your primary feed.

This is the part where I share parts of my exploratory feed. Feel free to steal parts of it to seed your own. The composition constantly changes at the rate of about one replacement every 3-4 months. And I don’t spend more than two days a week on it. And as a rule, I do not engage with twitter or online comment sections. But even without that, this has proven a valuable tool in understanding people of different political persuasions. And (by complete coincidence, maybe) as is typical of “conservatives,” the feed is heavy on individuals versus networks. For networks, right now I only jack into The Hill and Reason Magazine for mainstream-like takes. The Hill also hosts a daily news-aggregation and commentary show called Rising, hosted by Krystal Ball and Saagar Enjeti 17. They come from opposite sides of the aisle, and play off of each other rather well.

For news critical of the US government as a whole (as oppose to partisan news), I rely on The Intercept 18 and Max Blumenthal’s outfit, The Grayzone. The both of these have online video components, such as Aaron Mate’s Pushback, and Anya Parampil’s Red Lines. And The Intercept’s19 Glenn Greenwald (who was one of the first journalists involved with the NSA Snowden Leaks) hosts an interview/commentary show online called System Update. Here is a sample:

From here on it’s all individuals. In the mainstream, I follow anything written by Prof. Yascha Mounk. For a socialist/leftist/labor viewpoint I try and keep up with David Sirota, and for bold editorials, I use Matt Taibbi, who also co-hosts a podcast called Useful Idiots 20 with Katie Halper.

Besides all of these, I am interested in the views of the demography that switched sides. particularly those who consider themselves former democrats or former leftists (see the hastag #walkaway). Among them I discovered Cassandra Fairbanks, a former Bernie supporter who turned to the dark side sometime before the 2016 election. She writes for this awful publication called The Gateway Pundit, but she is generally reliable as a news source. As of June 2021, she is also said to be writing for an outfit called Timcast, though her work there appears to be behind a paywall.

I supplement all of this with a legal analysis by Canadian lawyer David “Viva Frei” Freiheit on Youtube. I find him very insightful, and he occasionally (perhaps weekly?) hosts a joint evening livestream/discussion with Robert Barnes, who is an American lawyer who is representing several US citizens in currently active, politically relevant court cases.

For a possible future addition, I am looking into the cynical Mr. Yasha Levine. And for a non-partisan window into extremism in protest movements, I'm relying on Jeremy Lee Quinn's Public Report.

As I’ve stated before, this is a forever evolving list. I hope the terms “primary feed” and “exploratory feed”, or some equivalents thereof catch on in regular parlance someday. Taking control of the exploratory process back from the algorithmic “recommendations” model should go a long way in addressing the perception gap, and hopefully contribute to fixing the polarization issue currently tearing this country apart.
